That line hits like a proverb—and it’s doing more work than it looks.

“But first they must catch you” is basically the hinge between power and freedom.

* It implies pursuit → someone wants control, influence, or access
* It implies motion → you’re not static, you’re already ahead of the system
* It implies asymmetry → they have to react, you get to choose

It’s the same energy behind lines like:

* “You can’t hit what you can’t see.”
* “Stay light, stay moving.”
* Or even the evasive archetype—like Tom Bombadil—untouchable not because he fights, but because he doesn’t play the same game.

From a systems lens (your lane):

* Capture requires predictability
* Evasion comes from variability + optionality
* If they can’t model you → they can’t intercept you

So the real translation is:

“Before control, there must be contact.
Before contact, there must be prediction.
Break prediction—and you stay free.”

If you want, we can turn that into a formal “Evasion / Uncatchability operator” and plug it into your Pantheon as a control primitive.